<div id="review_1479406553" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1479406553" />
    <a title="Luke" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/42048255-luke"><img alt="Luke" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1428742240p2/42048255.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1479406553?book_show_action=true">Dec 25, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Luke" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Luke" href="/user/show/42048255-luke">Luke</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1479406553" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5986563579434545870">Raspail has a crude form of prose. It is not refined but I cannot help but read on. This is not like most authors - I can put down the book sometimes too easily and not pick it up. The Camp of the Saints however, I simply couldn&apos;t put it down. Credit where credit is due - you will thoroughly enjoy this book, even if you disagree with it.<br/><br/>Yet Raspail is right. He is hyperbolic, certainly, but you cannot stretch out a book and detail every little migration. But the mass importation of the Third Wor</span>
  <span id="freeText5986563579434545870" style="display:none">Raspail has a crude form of prose. It is not refined but I cannot help but read on. This is not like most authors - I can put down the book sometimes too easily and not pick it up. The Camp of the Saints however, I simply couldn't put it down. Credit where credit is due - you will thoroughly enjoy this book, even if you disagree with it.<br /><br />Yet Raspail is right. He is hyperbolic, certainly, but you cannot stretch out a book and detail every little migration. But the mass importation of the Third World will bring forth disaster. His committees are eerily accurate - the multiracial commune? What about the Equality Commission in the UK, or in general, positive discrimination? Raspail is quick to emphasise this is not a prophecy. It's a parable, a tale. But we never heeded this parable. We heed the parables of Christ (they don't in this book, at least not in regards to the natives), but not this one oddly.<br /><br />The characters were fantastic. How couldn't you like Degrasses? How couldn't you like Calgues? This novel is simply fantastic. He is right on what he says and does it with a novel in mind. He never attempted to predict this or push an agenda. He wrote it over 18 months - a daunting task he said, and I can only sympathise - and did so purely out of his imagination and off of the hints implied to him, I expect. But he is far too accurate. And far too good. Definitely worth the read.</span>
  <a data-text-id="5986563579434545870" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


