<div id="review_1263067235" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1263067235" />
    <a title="Observer" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/42467935-observer"><img alt="Observer" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1263067235?book_show_action=true">Apr 24, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Observer" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Observer" href="/user/show/42467935-observer">Observer</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1263067235" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer985850275164857392">While it is understandable in 2015 to see this as an anti immigration novel that would be quite wrong. But liberals being liberals rarely get things right. More than anything the book is about income inequality. The masses swarming over France are the result not the cause. <br/><br/>It is quite true that income is becoming increasingly concentrated into fewer and fewer hands, and I&apos;m not talking about the US where most people living in poverty would be middle class or above in 3rd world nations. I&apos;m looki</span>
  <span id="freeText985850275164857392" style="display:none">While it is understandable in 2015 to see this as an anti immigration novel that would be quite wrong. But liberals being liberals rarely get things right. More than anything the book is about income inequality. The masses swarming over France are the result not the cause. <br /><br />It is quite true that income is becoming increasingly concentrated into fewer and fewer hands, and I'm not talking about the US where most people living in poverty would be middle class or above in 3rd world nations. I'm looking at the rest of the world. As income increasingly goes to fewer the population is increasing in the third world nations where there is less and less wealth while the people who have the wealth are shrinking in number. Compare birth rates in some African Nations to Italy's or that of Greece for example. Raspail has proposed what he sees as the inevitable result of ignoring this problem. If we look at the current immigration problems in the US and Europe, we begin to see he has it right. Desperate people with nothing to lose will do desperate things.<br /><br />There isn't enough money to simply spread it around, the usual liberal panacea, but the West could assert itself and stop patronizing dictators particularly those in places like Mexico that are oil rich with third world economies and instead, make life uncomfortable for them as they continue to squeeze their own people for their own benefit.<br /><br />What right do we have to do this? The same right of survival as Raspail describes.</span>
  <a data-text-id="985850275164857392" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


